    "product_smiles": [
      "CC(=O)C1=CC(=C(C=C1)O)O"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "Cl[Zn]Cl",
      "Cl"
    ],
    "rationale": "This reaction shows the acylation of a highly activated, simple aromatic compound (resorcinol) with a simple nitrile (acetonitrile) to form an aryl ketone. This is the classic textbook example of the Houben-Hoesch reaction, which is a variation of the Friedel-Crafts acylation specifically using a nitrile and HCl, often with a Lewis acid catalyst like ZnCl2. The reaction proceeds via an intermediate imine which is hydrolyzed to the ketone.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple, highly activated phenol (resorcinol) and a simple nitrile (acetonitrile). It avoids using generic benzene or toluene which could collide with standard Friedel-Crafts acylation examples. The use of a nitrile as the acylating agent is the defining characteristic of the Houben-Hoesch reaction, distinguishing it from other acylations that use acyl halides or anhydrides."
  }
}
